<h5>
Presentation 1: Food for Thought: Investigating Communication
Strategies to Counteract Moral Disengagement Regarding Meat
Consumption
</h5>

<p>
Authors: 
Benjamin Buttlar, Alisa Rothe, Simon Kleinert, Lena Hahn, &amp; Eva
Walther <br>
Speaker: Benjamin Buttlar (University of Trier)
</p>
<h5>Abstract
</h5>
<p>
Eschewing meat would benefit environmental sustainability, human health,
and animal welfare. Nonetheless, many people are reluctant to reduce their
meat consumption although they are conflicted about meat. These dietary
changes are often prevented by dissonance reduction in the form of moral
disengagement. Here, we tested a two-stage intervention strategy that
addresses these moral disengagement strategies: After watching videos of
animal welfare issues in animal agriculture (Stage I), activists used
scientific arguments to counteract people’s attempts to obviate their
responsibility and to deny the harm caused by meat consumption (Stage
II). In two field studies, we demonstrated that people’s evaluations of meat
changed and their willingness to reduce meat consumption increased
incrementally following Stage II. Importantly, Study 2 showed that the effect
of Stage II seemed to result from heightened attributed emotional
capacities to animals. We thereby offer a template outlining how moral
disengagement might be addressed to reduce meat consumption.
</p>
