<h5>
Presentation 2: Extending Perspective Taking to Non-Human Groups
</h5>

<p>
Authors: Ali Ladak, Jacy Reese Anthis &amp; Matti Wilks <br>
Speaker: Ali Ladak (Sentience Institute)
</p>

<h5>Abstract
</h5>

<p>
In two experiments we tested whether perspective taking, the active
consideration of the mental states of another individual, such as their
thoughts and feelings, has positive effects on attitudes towards non-human
groups. In Study 1, we found that taking the perspective of a farmed pig
(compared to staying objective and a neutral control condition) positively
affected moral attitudes towards animals via empathic concern and self-
other overlap. In Study 2, we found that taking the perspective of an
intelligent artificial entity positively affected moral attitudes towards artificial
entities as a group via the same mediators, though only when comparing
perspective taking to the objective condition. We did not find total effects of
perspective taking in either study. This was partly explained by competitive
mediation: in both studies, after controlling for the significant mediation
paths, we found evidence of positive effects of staying objective on moral
attitudes.
</p>
