<h5>Presentation 3: Harnessing Moral Psychology to Reduce Meat
Consumption
</h5>
<p>
Authors:
Joshua May &amp; Victor Kumar <br>
Speaker: Joshua May (University of Alabama at Birmingham)</p>
<h5>Abstract</h5>
<p>
Why does meat consumption remain high, despite increased awareness of
its negative impact on animal welfare? Weakness of will surely explains the
behavior of some consumers: acceptance of the ethical arguments doesn’t
motivate changes in behavior (the weakness model). However, we draw on
scientific evidence to argue that most consumers fail to be convinced in the
first place that they morally ought to reduce their meat consumption (the
belief model). We identify two key psychological mechanisms that lead
people to resist the ethical arguments. First, motivated reasoning allows
one to rationalize that animals don’t suffer or that their suffering matters
less. Second, social proof takes the behavior of others in one’s community
as evidence that meat consumption is normal, natural, and necessary. We
provide recommendations for how to harness these psychological
mechanisms to encourage reductions in meat consumption. Social change
on this issue thus requires socially-embedded reasoning.
</p>
