<h5>
Presentation 4: Meating conflict: Toward a model of ambivalence-
motivated meat reduction
</h5>
<p>
Authors: Shiva Pauer, Matthew B. Ruby, Bastiaan T. Rutjens, Grischa
Perino, &amp; Frenk van Harreveld <br>
Speaker: Shiva Pauer (University of Amsterdam)</p>

<h5>Abstract</h5>
<p>
An increasing number of people is concerned about the ethics of meat
consumption despite cherishing meat products. We examined whether the
desire to resolve such ambivalence about eating meat can motivate meat
reduction. A 6-day food diary with 7,485 observations in the German
general public showed a positive association of ambivalence with meat
reduction and identified sociodemographic predictors of meat ambivalence.
Study 2 showed that feelings of conflict, but not the ambivalent attitude
itself, motivated participants to eat less meat when participants
introspected on their ambivalence. Study 3 (preregistered) replicated this
experimental effect and demonstrated a serial mediation through
anticipated ambivalence resolution and information seeking. These findings
in diverse samples from the EU and US (total N=1,192) highlight that meat
reduction can result from the motivation to reduce pervasive feelings of
conflict. Our model of ambivalence-motivated meat reduction has important
implications for understanding how people progress towards animal-free
food choices.
</p>
