<h5>
Presentation 5: Mothers and daughters&#39; perceptions of climate
change issues, their reciprocal learning and parental resistance to
plant-based food
</h5>
<p>
Authors: Lorna Lamont &amp; Leyla De Amicis <br>
Speaker: Lorna Lamont (University of Glasgow)</p>
<h5>Abstract</h5>
<p>
Recently, many young people have organised pacific protests and strikes,
asking for radical political action to reduce the negative human impact on
the acceleration of climate change, all around the world. This research
aimed at exploring adolescent activists’ and their families’ perceptions of
climate change issues and reciprocal learning on this topic. Eight dyadic
semi-structured interviews involving female adolescent activists and their
mothers (six in the UK) were conducted. A thematic analysis extracted
three master themes (sense of responsibility, youth participation and
parental influence). Parental influence included two subthemes: support
and concern. Children’s adherence to a vegan diet was one main parental
concern. This study shows that these adolescents and their families
collaborated in climate change action, although some resistance emerged
regarding plant-based diets. Young people influenced their families with
their perseverance and provision of information, and this might lead to less
resistance towards plant-based food choices, in the future.
</p>

